Agents with Calls



The plot above shows call volume between 12:00AM October 15, 2021 and 11:59PM December 07, 2021. Total call volume is broken down into two sub-types of calls. The first is all calls more than one minute in duration. The second is winning calls.


To put these recent trends in context, the next plot shows call volume over the entire history of the playbook through 11:59PM December 07, 2021.




The next plot shows call win trend for the entire history of the playbook through 11:59PM December 07, 2021 The vertical gray lines denote playbook version change which may indicate the impact of playbook revisions on win rates.



To construct the plots below, we averaged each agents usage of the first checklist item and all checklist items for all calls between 12:00AM October 15, 2021 and 11:59PM December 07, 2021. Users are then binned according to these averages. In both plots, the ideal pattern is a tight distribution that is skewed to the right. A tight distribution implies minimal variation in usage across agents, while a rightward skew implies more usage.




Checklist Analysis

The plot on the left shows the probability that each checklist item is triggered across all calls more the 60 seconds in duration during the specified time period. Items are ordered sequentially from top to bottom as they appear in the playbook. An ideal pattern would be a smooth decline in probability from top to bottom.



This plot shows the winning percentage for each checklist item. That is, for all calls in which the item is triggered, what fraction result in a win? An ideal pattern in this plot is a smooth upward trend in probabilities through the checklist items. Items with unusually low winning percentages should be examined for possible revisions.



The plot above shows the top-10 most common checklist paths for winning calls. Each sequence of nodes represents the progression from the start of the call through the numbered checklist items. The node marked S denotes start of the call and the node marked with a W denotes the win marker. Several patterns should be present in many of the sequences. First, most checklist items should appear. If many wins occur without specific items being triggered, those items may not be important for wins. Second, node number should increase as the path progresses to the right. Examine the sequences for backtracking, both before and after the win. Backtracking may be a sign that the checklist items are ordered improperly.



This plot identifies potential skicking points in the sequential progression through the checklist items. When an item has an unsually small bar, it implies that once the item has been triggered, it is very difficult to move directly to the next checklist items.



This plot is similar to the plot above, except it measures the probability of each checklist item being the last checklist item that is triggered. Thus, items with large bars are closely associated with the call ending or failing.



Deck Analysis


The plot to the right shows the probability of hitting each of the top (up to) 20 deck items. These probabilities are specific to the requested time interval and reflect all agents that worked during that time period. Deck items considered important or common should appear in this plot.

This graphic shows the probability that a call will result in a win given each of the deck items has been triggered. Note that these are again the top (up to) 20 most commonly triggered items that appeared in the plot above. Examine the plot for patterns that are unexpected. Expectations should reflect an understanding of whether the deck item is a positive or negative signal when it is triggered. Items expected to be positive signals should have relatively large bars, while items expected to be negative signals should have relatively small bars.



When deck items are triggered, responses are suggested by decklist items. In some cases, agents do not offer any of the recommended language. In the graphic to the left, we report the fraction of deck trigger events that are not followed by any of the decklist items. The items included are again the top (up to) 20 most commonly triggered items.



In the graphic to the left, we report the win percentage of deck trigger events that are not followed by any of the decklist items. The items included are again the top (up to) 20 most commonly triggered items. Examine the plot for items with high win percentages as the decklist options for these may need to be reviewed.



Agent Feedback


This plot shows agent feedback on deck items since the creation of the playbook. Recall that users can leave thumbs up or thumbs down in response the specific deck items being triggered. Due to the somewhat infrequent nature of this feedback, the counts presented in the plot are weekly counts. Version changes are denoted with vertical gray lines, so inspect the plot for significant changes in feedback patterns that coincide with a version change.




Because feedback is item-specific, it is also valuable to check for items with relatively high negative feedback. The next plot contains the 20 deck items with the most negative feedback. Examine the plot for items with small bars (indicating negative feedback) and large bubbles (indicating frequent feedback).
